1) “Human nature as c” — refine it

In Relativity, c works because it’s:
	•	constant
	•	universal
	•	a hard constraint (nothing exceeds it)

“Human nature” doesn’t quite meet that bar. A tighter, more usable version would be:

Think of the “economic c” as:

bounded human constraints, not a single constant
	•	attention (finite)
	•	trust (slow to build, fast to lose)
	•	time preference (present vs future bias)
	•	coordination limits (friction in groups)

👉 These behave more like speed limits in different terrains, not one universal constant.

So your intuition is close—just upgrade it from:

“one fixed C”

to:

“a small set of semi-stable constraints that act like speed limits on systems”

That keeps it grounded and usable.

